                <opener>
                    <placeName>Edensor. | Kidbrook Grove. | Blackheath, London S.E.</placeName>
                    <date>7. December 1873.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>It is not easy to reject the notion that ‘twist’ has played a part in the history of Leaf-arrangement,—after an examination of the different species of <hi rend="underline">Gasteria</hi>, a South African genus which I first saw exhibited by D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Hooker at the soirée of the R.S. last spring, and which I have lately examined more carefully in the Cambridge Botanical Gardens.—<ref target="#foot.f1"/></p>
<p>Here is a figure of <hi rend="underline">Gasteria subnigricans</hi>,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> as seen from above:—</p> 
<figure rend="blockCentred width33"> 
    <graphic url="../images/DCP-LETT-9175-1.svg"/>
</figure> 
<p rend="left">—and here is a series of diagrams of the other species, similarly projected, numbers standing for leaves.<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p> 

